  "summary": {
    "one_line": "Pakistan's deadliest jihadist group, founded 2007 by Baitullah Mehsud, 2,500-6,500 fighters, Peshawar school massacre 2014 (149 killed, 132 children), led by Noor Wali since 2018, escalated 784+ attacks in 2024 (vs. 140 in 2021), operates from Taliban-protected Afghanistan sanctuaries, finances through extortion/drug smuggling/kidnapping, expanding to southern Punjab/Sindh/Balochistan.",
    "overview": "Tehrik-e Taliban Pakistan (TTP, Pakistani Taliban) is Pakistan's most lethal and operationally resilient jihadist organization, formed December 2007 as confederation of Pashtun militant networks under the command of Baitullah Mehsud to oppose Pakistani military operations in the Federally Administered Tribal Areas (FATA) and establish Islamic emirate under strict Sharia interpretation. With an estimated 2,500-6,500 fighters (UN/member state estimates vary; upper range more likely), TTP operates primarily from eastern Afghanistan's Nangarhar and Kunar provinces with sanctuary protected by Taliban regime (post-August 2021). The group is primarily composed of ethnic Pashtun jihadists from tribal areas, employing Deobandi Islamic ideology fused with Pashtun cultural code (Pashtunwali). TTP's most notorious operation was the December 16, 2014 Peshawar Army Public School massacre where six gunmen killed 149 people including 132 children—considered fifth-deadliest school massacre globally and the deadliest terrorist attack in Pakistan's history. Baitullah Mehsud, killed August 2009, was succeeded by Hakimullah Mehsud (killed November 2013), then Mullah Fazlullah (killed June 2018 US drone strike), and currently Noor Wali Mehsud (born 1978, leader since June 2018, designated SDGT September 2019). The group fractured multiple times (2014-2015 ISIS defections creating ISKP, 2014-2018 various splinter groups), but underwent reunification 2019-2020 under al-Qaeda mediation, re-consolidating to current strength. Post-Taliban takeover of Afghanistan (August 2021), TTP escalated dramatically: violent attacks increased from 140 in 2021 to 784 by 2024 (460% increase), with direct security force confrontations rising 470% and civilian attacks increasing 900%. TTP finances through Rs. 20 billion (~$100M) annual extortion economy (5-20% contractor taxation), drug smuggling (Afghan opium transit), kidnapping-for-ransom, weapons trafficking, and donations from madrassas. Geographic footprint expanded from traditional North Waziristan base to operational presence in Dera Ismail Khan, Peshawar, southern Punjab (19 attacks 2024), urban Karachi/Sindh, and Balochistan, indicating coordinated strategy to stretch Pakistani security forces. The group maintains loose al-Qaeda affiliation and coordinates with Taliban despite historical tensions. As of November 2025, TTP represents the primary internal security threat to Pakistan's stability.",
    "threat_level": "critical",
